      <hedline>
        <hl1>To Treat Women With Respect</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Claire Bierhorst letter on Brent Staples's June 26 column on Central Park assaults on women calls for public relations drive to address disrespectful verbal harassment women face daily on street</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Playing 'Catch and Grope' in the Schoolyard,'' by Brent Staples (Editorial Observer, June 26):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Playing 'Catch and Grope' in the Schoolyard,'' by Brent Staples (Editorial Observer, June 26):</p>
        <p>Since the Central Park attacks, my friends and I (we are in our 20's) have been talking about how women are treated in public. Several of us have been the victims of scary and embarrassing hit-and-run gropings that we cannot forget. These are crimes that should be reported. But we also need a public education campaign to address the disrespectful verbal harassment that women face on the street every day.</p>
        <p>Male role models can discuss the problem. Also, if enough women are direct with men, some men will start to question their own behavior. I suggest that women say ''stop humiliating me'' to men who harass them. I have started saying, ''I don't know you!'' on occasion and have received some good responses. One man even apologized.</p>
        <p>CLAIRE BIERHORST  Brooklyn, June 26, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
